"1398":"1398","about 1356":"circa 1356","Abt 1380":"circa 1380","High Harrogate, Yorkshire, Inglaterra":"High Harrogate, Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Markingfield Hall, Yorkshire, England":"Markingfield Hall, Yorkshire, England","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, England","Carlton Miniott, Yorkshire, England":"Carlton Miniott, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1356–1381":"about 1356–1381","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","1356–1381":"1356–1381","1340–1398":"1340–1398","1380–1415":"1380–1415","1315–1368":"1315–1368","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","before 1376":"before 1376","1396":"1396","1340":"1340","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","after 1368":"after 1368","1415":"1415","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1398":"1398","about 1356":"about 1356","Abt 1380":"about 1380","High Harrogate, Yorkshire, Inglaterra":"High Harrogate, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Markingfield Hall, Yorkshire, England":"Markingfield Hall, Yorkshire, England","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, England","Carlton Miniott, Yorkshire, England":"Carlton Miniott, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Miniott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Eugenie, Remy.","English (West Midlands): variant of   Minett  .","Altered form of French   Minot  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Minett","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>mignot</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>minot</i>, <i>mignot</i>, <i>minnot</i> ‘elegant, gracious, kind, courteous’. Compare French   Mignot  .","Altered form of French   Minet  . Compare   Minette  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Miniott was born about 1356, in Calverley, Yorkshire, England, her father, John Miniott, was 43 and her mother, Mrs. John Miniott, was 43. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Markinfeld. She died in 1381, at the age of 26, and was buried in High Harrogate, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1356–1381":"umbes 